    <h2>Analysis & Findings</h2>

    <p>
      The analysis shows that TikTok aesthetics play a significant role in how Gen Z expresses identity and connects with content. Trends like clean girl, coquette, and Y2K are not just visual styles, but ways for users to communicate personality and lifestyle. These aesthetics create a sense of belonging and influence what users consider appealing or relevant.
    </p>

    <p>
      Brands that align with these aesthetics tend to appear more relatable and current to Gen Z audiences. For example, brands like Rhode use a minimal and clean aesthetic that reflects the clean girl trend, while brands like Bershka incorporate Y2K-inspired visuals. By adopting these styles, brands can position themselves as part of the trend rather than separate from it.
    </p>

    <p>
      TikTok’s algorithm also plays a key role in amplifying these trends. Because content spreads quickly and reaches large audiences, certain aesthetics can become popular in a short period of time. This rapid exposure increases the visibility of both trends and brands, influencing consumer awareness and interest.
    </p>

    <p>
      However, the findings also suggest that authenticity is essential. Gen Z consumers are highly aware of when content feels forced or inauthentic. Brands that naturally incorporate aesthetics into their identity are more successful than those that try to follow trends without a clear connection to their brand values.
    </p>

    <p>
      Overall, the results support the idea that aesthetic-driven trends on TikTok have a direct impact on brand perception and consumer behavior. Visual identity, relatability, and authenticity all play a key role in how Gen Z engages with brands and makes purchasing decisions.
    </p>

